\chapter{Measures of Central Tendency}
\label{chap:ch3}

\section{Objective}

By the end of this chapter, you will be able to
\begin{itemize}
\item Explain the concept of measures of central tendency and interpret the 
information they provide.
\item Calculate, explain and compare modes, medians and means.
\item Understand other measures of central tendency
\item Select appropriate measure of central tendency according to the 
level of measurement and characteristics of the distribution.
\end{itemize}

So what is a measure of ``central tendency,'' and why do you need to recognize the center of a group of scores?  Suppose that you took a small test with five of your classmates.  The six of you took a 6-point test on Monday and the teacher returned the test on Wednesday.  She pauses at your table and gives you your paper with 4/6.  You do a quick calculation, 67\%.  What are you thinking?  Are you happy?  Are you upset?  That depends on how the five students did on the test.  There are three scenarios: 

\begin{itemize}
\item Everyone achieved 4 out of 6, [you're OK],
\item Everyone scored a 5 or 6 but you, [you're not OK], or
\item Everyone scored a 1, 2, 3, but you [you're very happy].
\end{itemize}

The method of comparing to a distribution is important in statistics.  We will define three common measures of central tendency.

\section{Three Common Measures}

The central tendency is a measure of where most of the data is located.

\begin{itemize}
\item mean
\item median
\item mode
\end{itemize}

\section{Mean}

The \emph{mean} (usually denoted as $\bar{X}$) is the arithmetic center of a distribution and is the most commonly utilized measure.  It reports the average value of a variable.

The strength and weakness of the mean.

\begin{itemize}
\item Strength -- All data from a variable are used to compute the mean.
\item Weakness -- The mean is affected by extreme values (\emph{outliers}).
\end{itemize}

