  There was a typo when 3 was entered into the dataset when the value should have been 30.  The value 3 will pull the \emph{mean} to the left.
  
  \end{itemize}

\item The mean, median, and mode are different values.  Notice that the mean will always be pulled from the median in the direction of the extreme values.
\end{itemize}

\section{Other Measures of Location}

The other measure of location are as follows:

\begin{itemize} 
\samepage
\item Percentage: point below which a specific percentage of cases fall.
\samepage
\item Deciles: divides distribution into tenth (10, 20, $\dots$, 90).  For example, children's height in age groups.
\samepage
\item Quartiles: divides distribution into quarters (25, 50, 75).
\samepage
  \begin{itemize}
  \item e.g., the median falls at the 50th percentile (or the 2nd quartile or the 5th decile.)
  \end{itemize}
\samepage
\item Mid-range: $ mr = \frac{Minimum + Maximum}{2} $
\samepage
\item Mid-hinge: $ mh = \frac{Q_1 + Q_3}{2} $
\samepage
\item Calculate a percentile
	\begin{itemize}
	\item Sort scores in order from low to high
	\item Multiply the number of cases (n) in the dataset by the proportional value of the percentile (for example: the 80th percentile is 0.8).
	
	\end{itemize}
		
	\item Example
		\begin{itemize}
		\item In a sample of 70 test scores, we want to find the 3rd quartile (or the 75th percentile),
		\item $70 \times 0.75 = 52.5$ is the 75th percentile.
		\end{itemize}
		  	
\end{itemize}
  
